{% extends 'guides/_guide_base.html.twig' %}

{% block guide_content %}
    {% set d1000 = distributions[1000] ?? null %}
    {% set d500 = distributions[500] ?? null %}
    {% set totalSolves = distributions|map(d => d.solvesCount)|reduce((carry, count) => carry + count, 0) %}

    <h1 class="h2 mb-3">How Long Does a 1000-Piece Puzzle Take?</h1>

    {% if d1000 %}
        {% set medianHours = d1000.medianSeconds // 3600 %}
        {% set medianMinutes = (d1000.medianSeconds % 3600) // 60 %}

        <p class="fs-lg">
            <strong>Across {{ d1000.solvesCount|number_format }} solo solves recorded on MySpeedPuzzling, the median time
            to finish a 1000-piece jigsaw puzzle is {{ medianHours }} hour{{ medianHours == 1 ? '' : 's' }} {{ medianMinutes }} minute{{ medianMinutes == 1 ? '' : 's' }}.</strong>
            Half of all recorded solves land between {{ d1000.p25Seconds|compactTime }} and {{ d1000.p75Seconds|compactTime }},
            and nine out of ten are done within {{ d1000.p90Seconds|compactTime }}.
        </p>

        <p>
            Most answers you will find to this question are guesses — usually somewhere between "5 hours" and "20 hours",
            published by people who never timed anyone. The numbers on this page are different: they come from real,
            timed solves tracked by the speed puzzling community on MySpeedPuzzling, measured with a stopwatch that
            counts active puzzling time. Nobody here is estimating.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 mt-4">The 1000-piece answer, in numbers</h2>

        <div class="row g-3 mb-4">
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1 text-primary">{{ d1000.medianSeconds|compactTime }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">Median time</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1">{{ d1000.p25Seconds|compactTime }}–{{ d1000.p75Seconds|compactTime }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">Typical range (middle 50%)</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1">{{ d1000.p90Seconds|compactTime }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">90% finish within</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1">{{ d1000.fastestSeconds|compactTime }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">Fastest recorded</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1">{{ d1000.solvesCount|number_format }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">Recorded solves</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-6 col-md-4 col-lg-2">
                <div class="card shadow-sm h-100 border-0">
                    <div class="card-body text-center">
                        <div class="h4 mb-1">{{ d1000.playersCount|number_format }}</div>
                        <div class="text-muted fs-sm">Puzzlers measured</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <p>
            One important nuance: these are <strong>active puzzling hours</strong>, not calendar time. The MySpeedPuzzling
            stopwatch is paused when the puzzler steps away, so "{{ d1000.medianSeconds|compactTime }}"
            means time actually spent placing pieces. If you do a 1000-piece puzzle over relaxed evenings, spreading the
            same hours across a week is completely normal.
        </p>
    {% endif %}

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">How long does a puzzle take, by piece count?</h2>

    <p>
        Piece count does not scale linearly. Doubling the pieces more than doubles the time: every new piece has more
        candidate positions, sorting takes longer, and images give proportionally less guidance per piece.
        {%- if d1000 and d500 %}
        In our data the median 1000-piece solve takes about {{ (d1000.medianSeconds / d500.medianSeconds)|round(1) }}&times;
        as long as the median 500-piece solve — not 2&times;.
        {%- endif %}
    </p>

    {% if distributions is not empty %}
        <div class="table-responsive mb-2">
            <table class="table table-striped">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th scope="col">Pieces</th>
                        <th scope="col">Median time</th>
                        <th scope="col">Typical range (middle 50%)</th>
                        <th scope="col">90% finish within</th>
                        <th scope="col" class="text-end">Recorded solves</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    {% for distribution in distributions %}
                        <tr>
                            <th scope="row">{{ distribution.piecesCount|number_format }}</th>
                            <td>{{ distribution.medianSeconds|compactTime }}</td>
                            <td>{{ distribution.p25Seconds|compactTime }} – {{ distribution.p75Seconds|compactTime }}</td>
                            <td>{{ distribution.p90Seconds|compactTime }}</td>
                            <td class="text-end">{{ distribution.solvesCount|number_format }}</td>
                        </tr>
                    {% endfor %}
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-muted fs-sm">
            Solo solves only. "Typical range" is the 25th–75th percentile: half of all recorded solves fall inside it.
        </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if d1000 %}
        <h2 class="h4 mt-4">What counts as fast?</h2>

        <p>
            "Fast" is relative, so here is where the field actually stands for 1000 pieces. Finishing under
            {{ d1000.p25Seconds|compactTime }} puts you in the fastest quarter of recorded solves. Under
            {{ d1000.p10Seconds|compactTime }} you are in the top 10% — solid speed puzzling territory. The fastest
            recorded solo 1000-piece solve on MySpeedPuzzling stands at {{ d1000.fastestSeconds|compactTime }}, set by a
            competitive speed puzzler on a familiar puzzle. Elite results like that typically come from repeat solves of
            a well-known image, which is exactly how competitors train.
        </p>

        {% if d1000.firstAttemptMedianSeconds is not null %}
            <h2 class="h4 mt-4">First attempt vs. repeat solves</h2>

            <p>
                Solving a puzzle you have already done before is measurably faster: you know the image, the tricky areas,
                and where to start. Looking only at solves marked as a first attempt
                ({{ d1000.firstAttemptCount|number_format }} of the recorded 1000-piece solves), the median is
                {{ d1000.firstAttemptMedianSeconds|compactTime }}, compared to {{ d1000.medianSeconds|compactTime }}
                across all solves. If you are timing your very first run of a fresh puzzle, expect to sit slightly above
                the overall numbers — that is normal.
            </p>
        {% endif %}
    {% endif %}

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">What changes how long it takes</h2>

    <ul class="list-unstyled">
        <li class="mb-3">
            <strong>Experience and technique.</strong> The single biggest factor. Puzzlers who track their times and
            solve regularly develop sorting systems, color memory, and piece-shape recognition that routinely cut solve
            times dramatically within their first year of deliberate practice.
        </li>
        <li class="mb-3">
            <strong>The image.</strong> A detailed illustration with distinct color zones solves much faster than a
            gradient sky, a repeating pattern, or — the classic nightmare — a single-color puzzle. Two 1000-piece
            puzzles can honestly be hours apart for the same person.
        </li>
        <li class="mb-3">
            <strong>Brand and cut.</strong> Piece shape variety, fit tightness, and print quality differ between
            manufacturers. Ribbon-cut puzzles (regular grid) reward speed technique; random-cut pieces slow down
            edge-matching but give more shape information.
        </li>
        <li class="mb-3">
            <strong>Setup.</strong> Table space large enough to lay out most pieces, good lighting, and sorting trays
            save a surprising amount of time — puzzlers lose minutes to re-scanning piles they have already searched.
        </li>
        <li class="mb-3">
            <strong>Familiarity.</strong> As the data above shows, repeat solves are faster than first attempts. Solving
            with a picture reference visible is also faster than solving "blind", which some competitions require.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">How we measured this</h2>

    <p>
        Every number on this page is computed from solve times recorded by real puzzlers on MySpeedPuzzling — timed with
        the built-in <a href="{{ path('stopwatch') }}">puzzle stopwatch</a> or entered manually and expressed as active
        puzzling time. We count solo solves only (no pairs or teams), exclude entries flagged as implausible, and
        exclude solves timed "from the unopened box", since unboxing and flipping pieces adds time that is not
        comparable. Percentiles are computed per piece count, so a 500-piece solve is never mixed into the 1000-piece
        statistics. You can read more about how MySpeedPuzzling computes community statistics on our
        <a href="{{ path('methodology') }}">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <p class="text-muted">
        Based on {{ totalSolves|number_format }} recorded solo solves on MySpeedPuzzling across
        {{ distributions|length }} piece-count categories. The statistics refresh automatically as the community
        tracks new solves.
    </p>

    <h2 class="h4 mt-4">Find out how long it takes <em>you</em></h2>

    <p>
        The median is a community answer — your answer takes one puzzle and a stopwatch. Time your next solve with the
        free <a href="{{ path('stopwatch') }}">MySpeedPuzzling stopwatch</a> (it works as a
        <a href="{{ path('puzzle_tracker_app') }}">puzzle tracker app</a> on your phone, with pause and resume), find
        your puzzle in the <a href="{{ path('puzzles') }}">puzzle database</a> to compare your time against everyone
        else who solved the same one, and see where you land on the
        <a href="{{ path('ladder_solo_1000_pieces') }}">1000-piece leaderboard</a>.
    </p>
{% endblock %}
